      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's really good to meet you. Coming back from plantar fasciitis takes real patience — the fact that you've already been cleared by your physio and are building things back up carefully says a lot about how you're approaching this.\n\nBefore I lay out the full plan, I want to make sure it actually fits your life. **A quick question first:** How has the foot been feeling on your recent runs? Any pain during, after, or the morning following? That'll help me calibrate how conservatively we start.\n\nThat said, here's everything you need to know about the plan I've built for you.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture\n\n**Your situation in plain terms:**\n\nYou have a strong pre-injury baseline — a 44:00 10K is solid fitness. But plantar fasciitis is one of those injuries that rewards patience above everything else. Your physio has cleared you for easy running only, 20 minutes max, no speed work. That's not a limitation to work around — it's the whole framework right now.\n\nYour recent training (2.5 km → 8.9 km → 6.4 km) shows you're already moving in the right direction. The slight dip last week is actually fine — consistency matters more than linear progression at this stage.\n\n**What this plan is NOT:** A return to your previous fitness. That comes later.\n**What this plan IS:** A structured, safe bridge back to consistent running — so that *future* you has a platform to build on.\n\n---\n\n## Guiding Principles for This Plan\n\n**1. Easy pace is non-negotiable — and here's why**\nYour physio-cleared pace is easy running only. Based on your VDOT of 46.5, that means **5:24–5:58/km**. This isn't \"going slow\" — this is the pace that drives aerobic adaptation while keeping mechanical stress low enough for healing tissue to tolerate. Plantar fascia responds poorly to pace-related ground reaction forces. Slower is genuinely faster right now.\n\n**2. Time over distance**\nDuring return-from-injury phases, we track *minutes on feet*, not kilometres. Distance can seduce you into pushing. Time keeps you honest.\n\n**3. The walking break rule**\nYour physio's instruction stands: **any foot pain = walking break immediately.** Not at the end of the run. Immediately. This isn't weakness — it's data collection and injury management.\n\n**4. 3 days/week, never on consecutive days**\nPlantar fasciitis needs 48 hours of reduced load between sessions. Your preferred structure (with Saturday long run) maps well to a **Tuesday / Thursday / Saturday** pattern.\n\n**5. 10% weekly volume rule**\nWe will not exceed 10% volume increase week-over-week. Given your active injury, we're starting more conservatively than that.\n\n**6. Deload every 4th week**\nVolume drops ~20% every 4th week. This is where adaptation actually happens.\n\n---\n\n## Your 8-Week Return-to-Running Plan\n\n### Pace Reference (easy running only)\n| Pace Type | Range | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Easy | 5:24 – 5:58 /km | **All runs use this range. Stay at the slower end if foot is tender** |\n| Walk breaks | As needed | Mandatory if any foot discomfort |\n\n> ⚠️ **No threshold, interval, or repetition work until you receive explicit physio clearance. These paces are listed in your profile for future reference only.**\n\n---\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC5 PHASE 1 — Foundation (Weeks 1–4)\n**Goal:** Establish consistent, pain-free running. Build tissue tolerance before building volume.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 1 — Reestablish the Pattern\n*Total target: ~8–9 km | 3 runs | Max 20 min each*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min | 5:45–5:58/km. Flat surface preferred. Walk break at first sign of discomfort. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 18 min | Same as Tuesday. Note how foot feels compared to Tuesday. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | Slight extension. Still fully easy. This is your weekly \"long run\" for now. |\n\n**Coaching note:** I know 20 minutes might feel almost embarrassingly short given where you've been. That's a completely normal feeling. But these runs are doing real work — your aerobic system doesn't know the session was short, only that it was consistent.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 2 — Confirm Tolerance\n*Total target: ~9–10 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min | 5:40–5:55/km if foot feels good. Otherwise stay at 5:58. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Push to full 20 min if Week 1 was pain-free. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | Focus on relaxed form. Short, light strides. |\n\n**Coaching note:** Week 2 is a confirmation week, not a progression week. You're asking your foot one question: *can we do this again?* If the answer is yes, we move forward.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 3 — Gentle Progression\n*Total target: ~10–11 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | Full duration. 5:35–5:50/km if comfortable. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Same. Pay attention to morning foot stiffness after each run. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | Final run of the week. Any cumulative fatigue in the foot? Note it. |\n\n**Coaching note:** Morning stiffness in the heel that lasts more than 10 minutes after getting up is worth flagging to your physio. First-step pain is a key marker with plantar fasciitis — not something to push through.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 4 — Deload \uD83D\uDD04\n*Total target: ~7–8 km | 3 runs (volume reduced ~20%)*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min | Deliberately shorter. This is intentional recovery. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min | Same. Enjoy the lighter load. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 18 min | Slightly longer than midweek. Still well below peak. |\n\n**Coaching note:** Deload weeks are where your body consolidates the adaptation from the previous three weeks. Runners often feel like they're losing fitness during these weeks — you're not. You're banking it.\n\n---\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC5 PHASE 2 — Building Consistency (Weeks 5–8)\n**Goal:** Extend total weekly time on feet. Maintain easy-only intensity. Prepare a platform for future structured training.\n\n> ⚠️ **Phase 2 assumes you are pain-free or have received updated physio guidance. If foot symptoms have increased, we pause here and I'll help you adjust.**\n\n---\n\n#### Week 5 — Extend the Long Run\n*Total target: ~11–12 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | 5:30–5:50/km. You should be able to hold a conversation. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Same. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 25 min | **First extension past 20 min.** Only if foot has been fully comfortable. Drop to 20 min if any doubt. |\n\n**Coaching note:** The Saturday extension is the key test this week. How does your foot respond in the 20–25 minute window? That's new territory for the healing tissue, and it's worth paying attention to.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 6 — Build Midweek\n*Total target: ~12–13 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 22 min | Small midweek extension. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 22 min | Same. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 27 min | Continuing gradual long run extension. |\n\n---\n\n#### Week 7 — Confidence Week\n*Total target: ~14–15 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 25 min | You're now running proper easy sessions. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 25 min | Same. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 30 min | **30 minutes is a meaningful milestone.** Celebrate that one. |\n\n**Coaching note:** At this point, if you've been pain-free for 2–3 weeks consistently, it would be worth a check-in with your physio about what comes next. You'll be approaching the territory where we *could* begin introducing more structure — but only with their green light.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 8 — Deload + Reflect \uD83D\uDD04\n*Total target: ~10–11 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Details |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | Back to basics. |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Same. |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 25 min | Easy close to the block. |\n\n**End-of-plan reflection:** Where is your foot? How do you feel overall? What does your physio say? The answers to those three questions determine what comes next.\n\n---\n\n## What Comes After Week 8\n\nIf you're pain-free and physio-cleared, the next block introduces:\n- Gradual duration extension beyond 30 minutes\n- Very gentle re-introduction of pace variation (not speed work — just natural fartlek-style effort shifts)\n- Eventual pathway back toward structured threshold and interval training\n\nYou have real fitness to return to, James. The 44:00 10K is yours — it doesn't disappear. It's waiting on the other side of this careful work.\n\n---\n\n## Weekly Self-Check Questions\n\nAfter every run, ask yourself three things:\n1. **During:** Any foot pain? (If yes — did I walk?)\n2. **After:** How does the foot feel in the first hour post-run?\n3. **Next morning:** First-step heel pain — present? Duration?\n\nIf you're seeing pain during runs more than once in a week, or morning stiffness lasting more than 10–15 minutes, that's worth flagging to your physio before continuing.\n\n---\n\n## A Note on Pacing\n\nI want to be direct about something: **5:45–5:58/km will feel slow.** You have the fitness to run considerably faster. But your foot doesn't have the tissue tolerance to match your cardiovascular system right now — that's the gap we're closing. Running at easy pace isn't a compromise. It's the actual tool.\n\n---\n\n**So James — before you lace up for Week 1: how has the foot been feeling on your runs so far?** Any pattern to when it bothers you — start of the run, end, the morning after? That'll help me fine-tune this as we go."
        }
      ],
